Wednesday, January 1, 1964

Watched the Rose Parade on the new color TV; also some Bowl games. Got a little work done on bibliography but not much else.

Thursday, January 2, 1964

At the office this morning. Spent most of the morning on personal affairs etc. At the library for a short time; also the banks. Worked on the company talk for next Saturday. The one used last February at Rancho Santa Fe under extensive changes.

Page Edit History:

Friday, January 3, 1964

At the office this morning. Worked most of the day on revising the speech to be made tomorrow. A longer job than I expected. Didn't finish it.

Page Edit History:
  • Szlyna 04/09/2013 12:28 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:09 PM

Saturday, January 4, 1964

Finished revising the talk "Lessons from the Past" this morning and then gave it this noon before the Company's Management Conference at the Vacation Village Hotel. Took about half an hour. I didn't think it went well; the reaction was more polite than anything else. I find I have to hold my slips up to be able to read them and this is annoying.

This afternoon went to the movie "Charade"at the Loma. Audrey Hepburn and Cary Grant. Very exciting. Enjoyed it thoroughly.

Sunday, January 5, 1964

Finally made a start on the Academic Press chapter and made some progress, but not as much as I should have. Too much tempting football: the Green Bay - Cleveland game at Miami; and the local Charger - Boston game which I listened to on radio.

Joe Copp was here and worked this afternoon on some of his Mexican Projects.

Did monthly accounting tonight.

At the office this morning.

More progress on morphology, but it goes pretty slowly.

Wednesday, January 8, 1964

Continued work on the Morphology section of the Academic Press project and made some progress. I find that when I am fresh I can work on something of this kind for about two hours, after which I become quite tired; that's the penalty of being 80.

At the office this morning. Short conferences with Dillin about franchise taxes.

Made a start on annual statement and income tax calculations this afternoon.

At the office this morning. Brief conference with Sinnott on PUC matters.

Conference with Mrs. Hiller on Natural History affairs.

Continued work on morphology and made considerable progress.

Went up to less for a short time to open a cabinet. Took a large part of morphology to Miss Molloy.

Friday, January 10, 1964

This morning at 8:30 went out to the ground-breaking ceremony at the Paradise Hills Branch Library. This lasted from 8:30 to 9:30. The Library Commission did not participate except to stand around.

We then had a Commission meeting from 10 to 10:40, after which I went to the office.

Went to Fred Krinzel's for dinner tonight. Met Judge Bruce (?) Brown and his wife.

Monday, January 13, 1964

At the office this morning.

Brought stamp inventory down to date.
Went to the library; had a conference with Miss Breed. She agreed to copy the Campo story as time permitted. I told her no rush. I took her the Fisher Opera House programs from Less place.

Worked for a while on the Academic Press project. Miss Molloy brought back the part she had copied -- almost everything down to date.

Prepared xmas cards tonight for Vinland's project. Prepared the finished part of Academic MS. for Shaw to look over.

James M. Clarke called me up about his proposed article about a naturalist for the San Diego Magazine. I tried to discourage the idea without much luck. Anyway told him I was too busy now, but he should me in mid-March.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 05/27/2014 04:43 PM
  • Szlyna 04/09/2013 12:55 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:09 PM

Tuesday, January 14, 1964

Went over to the Natural History Museum this morning and was interviewed by three representatives of the National Science Foundation in connection with the Museums application for a construction grant. It was brief -- only about 20 minutes. I described my collection and mentioned other reasons why S.D. should be a center of herp. research.

Then went up to the Zoo and delivered the Academic Press manuscript as far as completed to Shaw for his review; also the Xmas cards to Lisle Vinland.

Then down to the office and worked on senses for Academic Press but had not luck; I couldn't get into the swing. Went to the Bohemian Bakery to pick up bakery goods for Larry but couldn't get what I wanted so must return tomorrow.

San Diego Symphony concert tonight.

Page Edit History:

Wednesday, January 15, 1964

At the office this morning.

Long conference with Dillin on PUCmatters and fuel availability.
Went out once to buy bakery for Larry.

Hit the Academic Press project with better efficiency and made real progress.

Got a copy of Klemmer's important check-list today.

Took up to Miss Molloy the color section of the Academic Press MS.

My legs felt queer tonight; as if I didn't have full control over their movement.

by collecting, buying, and selling snakes. I discouraged him on the opportunities in that field but it took an hour and a half to wind up the conversation.
Went to a Scholia meeting tonight. James Tidwell talked on Politics and Words; the effect of slogans in politics, particularly elections. It was interesting.

Saturday, January 18, 1964

This was a day with much wasted time and little accomplishment, mostly my own fault.

I did make some progress with the Academic Press project but no nearly as much as I had hoped. Overhauled the rattle section and took the color part up to Miss Molloy.

Spent a lot of time in trying to repair the defective surtch in the library. In the early afternoon went to Sears to buy a new one; no luck they were sold out. Then I went out to North Park, very foolishly, and spent a full two hours going to one store after another trying to buy a replacement but none had the right kind.

Received today for comment from the U.C. Press at LA the copy of Fowlies "Snakes of Arizona". A long MS with many good points and many bad. This will take a lot of work. I am only supposed to comment, not edit; but I know it will work out.

At 4 (by appointment) a young man by the name of Ed Hayes came in for a conference. He was accompanied by a friend named Stafford or maybe Starkey. Hayes had stated over the phone that he wanted to discuss college courses leading to a herpetalogical career, but this was all a pose. He is married yet not even graduated from high school. What he really was interested in was the chance of making a living.

(Continued on Friday, Jan 17)

Saturday, January 25, 1964

Today I made real progress on the academic Project finishing the first drafts of Reproduction and Enemies.

Charity Ball at Coronado tonight. Went with Oscar and Clara Holloways and Milt Heller joined us at dinner. Also went to Tings Cocktail Party. Food was good and I ate too much.

Got home at midnight. Very tired. It was a very noisy affair. Didn't think much of the entertainment.

Tonight went to the San Diego Opera Guild Dinner at Coronado. We were host to 12 but the Millers didn't show up. Got pretty tired before we got home at 11:10. The entertainment was pretty good.

Saturday, February 1, 1964

This morning I finished the first long-hand draft of the Academic Press project. What a sap I was ever to have accepted this. It's already a month late and there still remains the copying first on yellow, and then double spaced white for the press. And also Shaw's overhauling, which he hasn't even started as he has his own chapter to do.

A lot of catching up today. Cleaned up a number of odds and ends.

Sunday, February 2, 1964

Got up this morning at 4 and gave the last part of Academic a final going over; also the letter to the Committee on Zoological Nomenclature on sirtalis.

Spent most of the day writing a letter to V.C. press about Fowlies ms. "Snakes of Arizona" and almost finished the first draft. Very long and involved.

Went over for dinner at Coronado Hotel with Col. Win Kelly + and his wife; also general Styer + wife. On the way over scraped the paint of a car owned by James R. Kilpatrick 10929 Calvert St. No. Hollywood. " " a 4 foot scratch only through the paint for a short distance.

Notes:

Szlyna

Unable to make out the first word in the last sentence. Used " " to show for the missing word.

David Hammond and Ralph Brown came in for an hour this afternoon to talk over some possible science projects. They are boys from San Diego High School.

Sunday, February 9, 1964

Spent most of today on borrowed material now available in the basement. I had completely forgotten what I had and its status. I found I am not very badly off. Everything had been checked except 6 specimens from Mesa Verde Nat. Park and 4 from Duellman at Kansas.
John Sloan had made the major counts on these.

I finished with the Mesa Verde material and now will only have to check the Kansas stuff: 2 trisereatus and 2 lepedus from western Mexico.

Jay came around for an hour this morning.

F.E. Russell came in tonight and we talked about all kinds of matters herpetological and otherwise from 7:45 until 10:15.

Thursday, February 13, 1964

At the office this morning.

Having had a letter from Mrs. Buckley expressing a willingness to check the Academic Press ms in its tripled spaced preliminary form. I spent much of the day rereading the ms. Also took Shaw the part he hasn't seen yet. He said he would read it tonight.

Our house piping sprung a leak in the ceiling of the pantry this afternoon. Got Klindts man up to look at it. They will go to work on the repairs tomorrow morning.

Page Edit History:
  • HerpVolunteer 06/02/2014 03:57 PM

Saturday, February 15, 1964

Started for Palm Springs this morning at 10:15; arrived at Palm Desert at 1:00 and had had some lunch. Arrived at El Encanto, Palm Springs at 2 PM. Went by way of 395, Anza, and Palms to Pines Highway. 139 miles.

Gave the Rattlesnake talk at the Palm Springs Desert museum. There was a very slim crowd as they charged admission -- adults 1.00; kids .50. Maybe 30 to 35 present all told. Very few questions asked except a few by kids. I talked for 55 minutes 8:12 to 9:07; then 5 minutes for questions. Forgot to ask for a glass of water at the speakers place and nearly got into a bad coughing spell. There was certainly no pep to the presentation. They have a fine auditorium.

After the talk, although I was very tired, we went to Grace Lines (the korean) home with a couple of other people for ice cream and cakes.

Got home at almost 10:30.

Page Edit History:

Sunday, February 16, 1964

Some rain and wind this morning at Palm Springs. Went home via 111, 60, and 395. Started at 9:35 and arrived home at 12:30. Miles this way 143 so only 4 miles difference via Palms to Pines.

Spent the afternoon catching up.

Thursday, February 20, 1964

At the office this morning.

Had a conference with Sinnott on PUC matters.

on which I had started the corrected ms. of hybrids. I knew there must be a set of sheets somewhere, because the corresponding Xerox blanks were missing. Saturday, March 14, 1964

Today I finally got back to the revision of Rattlesnakes after a virtual discontinuance since Dec. 3 of last year, when I turned aside to do the Academic Press Prjoject. This is fantastic for I have dropped the revisionary work for over 3 months. During this time I have kept up on odds and ends that affect Rattlesnakes but no major revisionary work has been done.

Of course the Academic Press project has been done. Of course the Academic Press project has been the principal tangent, but there have been many others, such as income tax, the sirtalis problem etc, all very time - consuming; and the worst of it is that they never cease. For example yesterday Brattstrom's Crotalidae paper arrived in galley proof for checking -- another long job. And I find it very difficult to pick up Rattlesnakes after the long job, because I can't remember what I was doing or why, or where the pertinent data is to be formed.

The situation is a mess and it is clear that if I can't avoid some of the correspondence and problems that are dropped in my lap, the revision of Rattlesnakes will never be finished. Meanwhile the UC press has no more copies available for sale.

The first trouble that I ran into in my endeavor to pick up hybrids where I had left off, was that I couldn't find Xerox pp. 207-216.

(Continued on Mar. 12)

Thursday, March 26, 1964

This morning started for Pomona at 9:40. It was clear and cool, a fine day. Arrived at the stuffed shirt at Upland at 11:50. Had a fine lunch there with GG and Clara Torrence, who had gone up with us. We took a room at the Upland Motor Hotel, so we were fixed for the night. Cecil Badgley came over from Pomona and guided us in. I was scheduled to talk on Rattlesnakes; the first thing we did was to get oriented. The talk was to be at Sever Hall at 4:15 preceded by tea and cakes at 3:45. Called Rickey and invited him.

Dr. Dwight L. Ryerson was the presiding officer at the talk. I talked for about an hour, followed by 15 minutes of questions. There were between 75 and 100 present. I think it went quite well as they were sufficiently interested to ask a large number of questions. Voice was kind of rough. Must remember to ask for water.

After the talk we went for dinner with Cecil where there was a large crowd of old folks. Then to Cecil's room for a chat for about an hour. Then back to Upland. Pretty tired.

Luncheon meeting of the Directors of the California State Chamber of Commerce and local business men, particularly the Ambassadors Club. Met a lot of people who had been members of the State Chamber directorate when I was. Sat at the head table taking the place of someone who failed to show up.

George Lindray now of Cal Acad called this afternoon and stayed for about an hour. He was down on Cooper Club business and came in while I was babysitting.

Saturday, April 18, 1964

This was another day of little accomplishment toward my major objective, namely the correction of Rattlesnake. Of course I am awaiting a decision by the UC Press. I did get some letters written and some new bibliographic material accessioned.

Went to the Arthur Johnson's for lunch, which of course was very good. Didn't get home until 3. Got a short nap. At 5 PM Dale Wood, the conversational non-stop champion, and John Daird Goodman, of Redlands College with his wife came in to call. We discussed various herpetological trivia for an hour.

Went to Scholia at 6:30. Henry Jansen discussed "The Twin Cultures -- A Snow Job". I didn't get too much out of it and my discussion was poor. Got home at 10.

A tiring day.

Sunday, May 3, 1964

Got a good start today and finished up a lot of odds and ends. Got started on rereading Chapter 10, Reproduction and made good progress.
Wrote a letter to GG and took it to the post office for airmail.

(May 4th, continued)

Next went to the Riverside Municipal Museum in the basement of the Police Station; it was locked and I went back and forth to the Public Libaray, where I could keep dry and warm, three times. Finally I was told by a gal in the Police Station that the meetings were held upstairs, so I went up and waited. Nobody showed up. The time for the meeting had arrived so I began to get nervous.
Went outside to look around in the rain and finally R.K. Pidot, the museum man who had invited me, recognized me (he had been at the Palm Springs meeting) and told me the meeting had been moved to the auditorium of the Mission Inn. This was a good meeting place, warm and comfortable and quite a crowd was already on hand. Altogether there were between 175 and 200 present including lots of kids.

After the talk there were many questions until finally the chairman invited those who had enough to go home and the questions to day for more, which they did, crowding around for

(Continued on May 2)

Monday, May 4, 1964

Finished reviewing Chapter 10, Reproduction, in the early morning hours. Started on Chapter 11. Couldn't sleep worth a cent last night.

Down at the office this morning. Wrote to GG. Home to lunch a little early; then one of the men in the garage took me down to the Greyhound Bus Station and took my car back to the garage. It was cold and windy so I took my over coat, besides baggage. The trip was an express run to Riverside; took only 2 hours. Got a little sleep but couldn't read as there is too much vibration. It continued cold and windy with some rain.

Upon arrival at Riverside as I am completely ignorant about the town, I saw a hotel sign "The Plaza" only a half block from the Bus Station and put up there. It was a terribly unsatisfactory and dirty place but I made the best of it. At least it had a bath but I didn't take a chance on using it next morning. I found later that the Mission Inn was only two blocks from the Bus Depot, but this would have been too far for me to haul my baggage anyway.

Rested for a while; then went out looking for a market to buy oranges and rolls for breakfast but no luck.

Went to supper at the Inn. Food was good but hate those dark, candle-lit, doggy places.

(Continued on May 3rd)

Tuesday, May 5, 1964

Woke up early today in plenty of time to have some hot cakes for breakfast in the Bus Depot. I didn't take a bath or shave because the bathroom was so dirty.

The trip back was much above then the one coming up as they stopped at a lot of towns off the highway such as Perris, Elesinore, Murrieta, Temecula, Fallbrook, Bonsall, Vista, San Marcus, and Escondido. Altogether it took from 7:43 until 11:00 AM and was pretty tiring, but at least not as bad as driving. Took a taxi to the office then home, where I tackled the mail and newspapers, which took all the rest of the day and evening.

Had to turn down an invitation to talk at a doctors meeting tomorrow might account of conflicting engagement.

Wednesday, May 6, 1964

At the office this morning. Spent the entire morning checking the two speeches (Rattlesnakes and Population Explosion) To be delivered tonight and tomorrow noon.

Went out to Del Mar in the evening and gave the Rattlesnake talk to the Del Mar Parent Teacher Association. The festivities were supposed to be started at 7:30 but they didn't get underway until about 8. Then there were reports and announcements that took quite a while, followed by concerts by classes of the school band.

I got started about 8:30. The attendance was about 200 of which more than half were kids and by the time I got underway they were of course tired and restless. I think I talked for about half an hour; after which there were a few questions. But most of the parents wanted to get the kids home and in bed, for which I certainly didn't blame them. I got home at 10:10.

Thursday, May 7, 1964

At the office until 11 this morning. Worked over the speech on the Population Explosion and made a number of changes.

Then went out to La Jolla and delivered the talk to the 12:30 club, a group of about 25 retired men. They listened attentively and I think it went over fairly well, although they asked no questions. Took about 55 minutes. A number expressed satisfaction after the meeting.

I unfortunately repeated a mistake I have made in the past -- attempting to read the slips when placed on too low a rostrum which was waist high. I couldn't see the writing clearly enough and as a result fumbled a lot of statements. After I had sense enough to hold the slips up in my hand above the rostrum. I did better but it wasn't too hot.

I was thoroughly tired out when I got through -- just about able to navigate. Three speeches in so short a time was clearly too much. I got home at 3 o'clock and felt better after a snooze.

GG's plane was late; started late. Due 9:08; got in at 11:30; got home at 12.

Friday, May 15, 1964

At 11:40 showed them some areas of the Library until 12:20.

Conrad Mollath of the U.C. Press phoned this afternoon and said he had been delegated by Fringe and Lillienthal to make some estimates of costs of a 2nd Edition compared with a 2nd printing and supplement. I told him I was more than ever convinced that a second edition was the only solution from the readers stand point. He will come down at 9 AM June 11th to talk it over.

Received today 2 separates from the National Medical Library.

Tonight went out to dinner at the La Jolla Country Club and guests of Carman Luce. Dinner given by a La Jolla Woman's Group to advance support of the LA Symphony. Went out with the Whitneys. Entertainment by Marais and Miranda, the balladeers. Very enjoyable indeed.

In the afternoon went out with Miss Breed and other librarians to the ground-breaking ceremony of the Allied Gardens Benjamin branch library. This took from 3 to 4. I spoke briefly (one of several) and did rather poorly.

June 11, Continued

A long interview by a Tribune reporter this afternoon on Rattlesnakes by phone.

Went to a dinner party at the Cuyamaca Club tonight given by the Malcolm Loves fro the Charles Luckman's. A large noisy party with good food. Couldn't hear a thing.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/15/2014 03:29 PM
  • Szlyna 04/29/2013 11:31 AM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:09 PM

Thursday, June 11, 1964

Did not go to the office this morning. Had a scheduled meeting to discuss the republication of Rattlesnakes with Conrad W. Mollath, Production Manager of the U.C. Press. He was due at 9:30 but did not arrive until about 10:20. We had a very interesting and fruitful discussion. Went over the ms as far as I have gone and he took down much material which will aid him in reporting probable costs to Fringe.

At least it was definitely decided to abandon the original plan for a second printing with a supplement. If they go ahead at all it will be a second Edition with no supplement. Everything new or revised will be incorporated in the text.

Our discussion lasted until about 1:30 including lunch at Dorothy's of ten. He expects to report to Fringe about June 27; and I should get an answer about Aug. 1. Everything will depend on cost estimates, but at least I know which scheme will be used if they go ahead at all. So I can proceed with the ms and take a chance that something will be worked. Went down to the office about 3 and cleaned up my desk.

Continued on June 10.

Exhibits for public benefit
Maintenance and additions to the scientific collections
Publication of scientific papers
Maintenance and expansion of the library
Equipment -- facilities and apparatus -- for scientific work.

This noon attended a joint meeting of the Zoo Trustees and the Stanford Research Institute group that will work on my survey. Gave them my opinion with references to their sounding out those Trustees against the San Pasqual development as well as the Zoo staff, which is all pro San Pasqual.

Fin Russell called late this afternoon about a very serious horridus bite he was treating. Man had been bitten at the Hermosa Reptile farm.

At Cottons met a printer, a distant relative, named Rice. I understand he is printing Russell's venom bibliography. He made a remark to the effect that the U.C. Press was hard up for money and that some works (Kroeber's Anthropology for one) were being reprinted and marketed by other institutions.

Tuesday, August 25, 1964

Meeting of the Gas Co Directors this morning 8:30 - 9:30. Combination with Sherman Chickering and Bert Lynch in San Francisco. For opening of bids for 20 million of debentures. Blyth won (there were 6 other bidders) with a cost of money to the company of 4.54% par at 4 1/2 to the public. The bid was 99.31. Accepted. Other matters were discussed briefly.

Meeting of the KW directors at my home 12 to 3 in the afternoon.
Meeting of the Natural History Society Directors 4 to 5:30. Election of officers for the coming year and appointment of committees.

I shot off my mouth at some length about the objectives of the society, especially designed for the new directors. Some of the objectives were in opposition to those of Yale Davison. I don't think this went over too good.

Monday, September 14, 1964

At the office this morning. Considerable miscellaneous work.
Meeting at the Zoo and lunch and a bus ride with City Council and Board of Supervisors, 12:15 to 1:30.

Meeting of Directors Natural History Museum 3:30 to 6:15 mostly to discuss the scope of the museum's activities and particularly Davison's NSF Galapagos project. I presided in Norman Lawson's absence and talked altogether too much for a presiding officer. Most of the new directors were there and they voted (and talked) as a block for the new program. The discussion was quite better at times and the old timers, such as were there, were completely snowed under.

Dinner at home for the family, particularly Gracie and Larry who are shortly starting for college. There were about 22 present. I was very tired because of having had no afternoon rest, so I was a poor host.

Saturday, September 19, 1964

At last today I got the U.C. Press answer to my letter of Aug. 17 about the problems of the revision of Rattlesnakes and their selection of the course, among the several alternatives I had suggested.
They picked the completely new edition. It would sell for $30.00; this could involve the Zoo's putting up $18,000.00 which they would get back at $10.00 per set sold. 2000 sets would be printed so the problem must be put up to the Zoo.

Wrote letters today. Larry came down to lunch. We watched TV for a while. I must quit watching game of which I am really interested in the outcome.

Fixed dining room bell which took much longer than I expected.

Tuesday, November 10, 1964

This morning GG had a bad cold and we almost gave up going to the opera in Los Angeles and considered various ways in which our tickets might be disposed of. Went down to the office for a short time. Came home and as GG was feeling a little better, we decided to go. Took quite a while to pack up and finally got started at 11:20. Stopped at the dress-makers at La Jolla for a try-on and also at a pan-cake joint for lunch. I drove all the way. It rained quite hard through most of Orange Co. Arrived at the Parkway Motel at about 3:30. Rested and then went to Carl's for dinner. Started somewhat late so we had to rush but arrived in plenty of time. Our seats were not so good as previous years; too many season ticket holders come first, I presume. We had A 40-42.

The opera was Traviata and the place was jammed. People outside trying to buy tickets from incoming audience. The performance was excellent with Joan Sutherland, Robert Ilosfalvy as Alfredo and Eberhand Waechter as the elder Germont. Sutherland of course doesn't look the part; she never was good looking and she is getting heavy; her voice a little rough in spots still it was a first class performance.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/19/2014 05:26 PM
  • Szlyna 07/10/2013 06:35 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:09 PM

Wednesday, November 11, 1964

Rested most of the morning. Found the Library was closed because of the holiday, so I had brought up a lot of items quite in vain. Went down town at noon. We parked at the Pershing Square garage, which was a mistake. It's hard to get out; very inefficient. Had a good lunch at the Baltimore. Went home and got more rest. GG, feeling somewhat better, went out and did a little shopping.

Went to Carls for supper; allowed plenty of time so that we could park on the street. Found a new motel, the Vegabond, quite near the Shrine Auditorium; easy walking distance. Will be very handy if future operas are held at the Shrine. Also a good place to eat here.

The opera was Turandot, a very enjoyable affair despite the horrible plot. Our seats were slightly better than last night, but not much A 36-38. Right near the timpani + percussion which was interesting and didn't interfere too much. The cast included Pilar Lorengar as Lui, Franco Tagliavini as Calaf, Georgio Tozzi as Timur, and Brigit Nilisson as Turandot. It was very enjoyable. The house was packed and surprisingly, much more enthusiastic than last night. They stood up and applauded wildly. Went home in the rain.

Thursday, November 12, 1964

This morning started home at 8:30 and arrived about 11:15. An uneventful trip. The freeway was heavily crowded as far south as Anaheim but fortunately no pileups. A few sprinkles of rain around Santa Ana. I drove.

Unloaded and went down to the office before noon. Talked to Phil. Heard Joe Sinnott had been looking for me, but didn't see him. Miss Breed called about Library Commission meeting tomorrow at College Heights Branch; and Sherman Platt about the U.C. Press contract. Gave him an inadequate answer.

Spent most of the afternoon catching up on reading and made some progress.

Went to the opera tonight. A twin - kill: Gianni Schicchi with Tito Gobbi, Lee Venora, and Howard Fried in the principal parts; and Carmina Burana with Mary Costa and Raymond Wolansky. We had our usual front-row seats. I found both performances very enjoyable although they are anything but standard opera fare. Still pretty tired from the trip.

GG's cold better but by no means cured.

After that a talk on electrophoresis blood analyses by the starch gel method to show mammal relationships. It was way over my head. I didn't wait for the second talk. A long called walk back to my car as I didn't know the short cut in the dark.

Wednesday, December 9, 1964

At the office this morning. Did some addressing of Xmas cards and also filing. Again went over the Pliny talk and decided the type written copy wouldn't do; well use the hand-written slips of which I copied some. I should have done more.

A little after noon Conrad Mollath of the U.C. Press called up. He said they were returning all the glossy prints etc that they had up there. New prints of all half-tones will be made, so I can choose the best regardless of what appeared in the First Edition. I told him I was just leaving town so he said he would write me the answers to all the questions in my last letter.

Started for Claremont + Scripps College at 2:15. Got to Pomona at about 4:30 via US 395 and U.S. 60; but after getting to the town of Pomona we got completely lost and spent a lot of time and miles looking for Scripps. Finally got there and went to the Faculty Club House where we were given every attention and a fine room by a Mrs. Wilson formerly of San Diego.

Had Dinner at the Inn with Cecil, Gracie, and Christine Oatmen. Found our mean was also paid for--that is 3 of us.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/26/2014 03:22 PM
  • Szlyna 07/10/2013 07:40 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 01:09 PM

Thursday, December 10, 1964

Had a good night's rest and breakfast was sent in. They certainly have treated us royally.

Went down to the hall, where I was to speak and met Dr. Curtis, President of Scripps, Miss Drake the Librarian and others.

The Pliny talk went off on schedule and although I had a good rostrum, light, and amplifier, I couldn't read many of the slips, wherever the writing was small or poor. So there was, unfortunately a lot of stumbling and fumbling. The girls (the audience was almost exclusively Scripps College girls) seemed to like it OK but I thought it was a bust - a very sloppy job of frequently jumbled reading.

After the talk we went to lunch with Dr. Curtis, Cecil, Miss Drake, and about 10 of Gracie's girlfriends. This was restful and OK; by this time I was very tired, especially from the talk Dr. Curtis gave me quite unexpectedly as an honorarium a check for $100. This I endorsed to the Scripps Library and presented to Miss Drake.

Got started home about 1:30 and arrived at 4. GG drove all the way. Got a little close to the right side of the road at one spot and hit the raised berm. Fortunately we bermed back to the road + no damage was done.

Spent the evening unpacking + catching up with the newspapers. Tired but no cystitis troubles.

Pretty tired after a day with no rest.

Gracie and Larry came to dinner tonight.

Chuck Wagon

Midway Chuck Wagon
Midway Drive at Rosecrans
San Diego 6, Calif.

Delicious choice of prime ribs -- all you can eat for $2.29 is the slogan of the Midway Chuck Wagon. Customers are invited to dine "Chuck Wagon Style" in a quaint Western atmosphere. Enjoy your favorite cocktails in the unique Gaslight Bar or the Longbranch Saloon where top names in the entertainment world will entertain you. The policy of giving the people what they want in quality... price... and service... has made the Midway Chuck Wagon the outstanding eating and entertainment attraction of the West.
